umnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Discord Grows After Russia Fire Kills Dozens of Children; Rumors spread about tragedy at Siberian mall, as Putin visits survivors, blames corruption</Para></Headline></Title><Corrections fid="cx"><Para>Corrections &amp; Amplifications</Para><Para>Televised reports of a Tuesday visit by Mr. Putin showed the Russian leader as sympathetic An earlier version of this article misspelled the Russian president's surname. (March 28, 2018)</Para></Corrections><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>MOSCOW—Russian officials said a shopping-mall fire Sunday in the Siberian coal-mining city of Kemerovo killed 64 people, but many people aren't buying that account.</Para><Para>Some Russians, shocked by video from the fire, agitated by online reports and habitually suspicious of official accounts, said the tragedy was far worse. A few thousand people gathered on Tuesday outside Kemerovo's city hall for a vigil that turned into a daylong rally of sorts, and was broadcast live online.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The fire has presented President Vladimir Putin with the first major bout of public discord since he <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-wins-fresh-six-year-term-in-russian-election-1521396635">secured a new six-year term</ELink> in an election this month.</Para><Para>The lack of trust in authorities' version of <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-mall-fire-kills-at-least-64-1522072473">what happened in Kemerovo</ELink> shows the flip side of the Kremlin's tactic of spreading multiple official accounts of Russian action abroad, such as blaming the British government for <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-poisoned-ex-russian-spy-sergei-skripal-the-kremlin-has-many-theories-1521889201">the poisoning of a former double agent in England</ELink>.</Para><Para>Televised reports of a Tuesday visit by Mr. Putin showed the Russian leader as sympathetic and taking aim at the corruption he said was to blame for the disaster.</Para><Para>The fire on Sunday afternoon tore through the Winter Cherry mall in Kemerovo, a city of a half-million inhabitants some 2,000 miles east of Moscow. Firefighters spent hours battling the blaze as it gutted the top floors of the five-story building, which housed shops, a bowling alley, an ice rink and cinema.</Para><Para>Harrowing personal stories from Kemerovo have shocked a nation hardened to such disasters. Security-camera footage showed adults and children running in all directions as flames and smoke quickly filled a hall. Another video showed a boy jumping from a fourth-story window through billowing smoke and landing with a thud.</Para><Para>Russian media have recounted how children locked in the cinema desperately messaged relatives to say they couldn't breathe. One man described how he lost three daughters, his wife and his sister. Most of the victims were children, officials said.</Para><Para>Public distress was further stoked by accounts shared on social media from people who said they were witnesses or relatives and knew that hundreds had died.</Para><Para>Thousands poured onto the streets in cities across the country on Tuesday evening to remember the victims of the fire in vigils approved by the authorities, but with an undercurrent of anger.</Para><Para>At the Kemerovo rally on Tuesday, amid rumors that the real death toll stood around 350, a group went to a cold storage-facility, the city morgue and the cemetery, following rumors in search of dozens of hidden corpses.</Para><Para>They reported back that the official death toll held up. "There was nothing there apart from fish and ice-cream, just as it should be," a bearded man in a green coat said after visiting the cold-storage facility.</Para><Para>Some in the crowd howled derision and called for the ouster of the governor.</Para><Para>"Where's the king?" one man shouted into the microphone, referring to Mr. Putin. "He was only just elected, let him come here."</Para><Para>On Tuesday, Mr. Putin laid flowers at the scene, visited survivors and held a meeting with senior officials, where he blamed the fire on the "criminal negligence and sloppiness" of local bureaucrats and the mall's managers.</Para><Para>The events in Kemerovo are unlikely to pose a serious threat to the 18-year rule of Mr. Putin, whose approval ratings stand around 80%. The president on Tuesday sought to divert the focus of anger about the fire.</Para><Para>"You can't get any official documents without money," Mr. Putin said. "And if you pay they will sign anything. That's the trouble. And they didn't give a damn about people's safety," he told the officials.</Para><Para>The country's top criminal investigator, Aleksander Bastrykin, told Mr. Putin that the fire was most likely caused by an electrical fault. The fire-alarm system was turned off, and the doors in the cinema has been locked, perhaps to prevent children without tickets from sneaking in, he said. Five people, mostly top managers of the mall, had been detained, he said.</Para><Para>People started gathering Tuesday morning on Kemerovo's main square. The crowd swelled to a few thousand, the largest rally in the city since miners' protests over unpaid wages in 1992, locals said.</Para><Para>Aleksandra Mamulat, 33 years old, said it was the first time she had been to a rally, but she wanted to express condolences and support for those affected.</Para><Para>"We weren't afraid of police and didn't just talk in our kitchens or post on the internet, but came to protest," said Ms. Mamulat, who works for a cosmetics firm. "We wanted to show that we have had enough, that we want the truth and don't want it to happen again."</Para><Para>Ms. Mamulat said she believed the official death toll. "Trust in authorities is so low that people think they are lying even when they aren't," she said.</Para><Para>State television largely ignored the crowd on the square, which the regional governor, Aman Tuleyev, told Mr. Putin consisted of 200 troublemakers. But it carried extensive coverage of Mr. Putin's visit, where he chided officials and consoled ordinary folk in a manner that has helped him avoid opprobrium during earlier catastrophes.</Para><Para>"Where's the mayor?" he snapped when an official told him that it was municipal authorities that handed out permits for the building.</Para><Para>Asked about a perceived lack of official information, Mr. Putin told a group of locals that 100 investigators were working on the case, and urged them to wait for official results.</Para><Para>"Social networks are a murky source," he said.</Para><Para>Write to James Marson at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:james.marson@wsj.com">james.marson@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-poisoned-ex-russian-spy-sergei-skripal-the-kremlin-has-many-theories-1521889201">Who Poisoned Ex-Russian Spy Sergei Skripal? The Kremlin Has Many Theories</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-mall-fire-kills-at-least-64-1522072473">Russian Mall Fire Kills at Least 64</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putins-election-victory-magnifies-deep-divide-in-russias-political-landscape-1521463334">Putin's Election Victory Magnifies Deep Divide in Russia's Political Landscape</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/better-off-than-their-parents-why-russias-youth-are-backing-putin-1521205201?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=3">Better Off Than Their Parents: Why Russia's Youth Are Backing Putin</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-expels-60-russian-officials-over-poisoning-of-ex-spy-in-u-k-1522071201">U.S., Allies Expel Scores of Russians in Response to Former Spy's Poisoning</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Jam